      "content": "I'll focus on the science. The enzymatic breakdown of starches by amylases in a sourdough starter is a crucial step in the fermentation process. Amylases, specifically alpha-amylase, break down starches into shorter-chain carbohydrates, such as maltose and dextrins. These products are then further fermented by the yeast, producing more fermentable sugars.\n\nThe pH of the starter plays a significant role in the activity of amylases and the subsequent fermentation process. Amylases are most active at a pH range of 5.5-6.5, which is slightly acidic to neutral. As the yeast consumes the starches and produces carbon dioxide, the pH of the starter decreases, creating an environment that favors the activity of amylases.\n\nRegarding hydration, a higher water content can accelerate the fermentation rate. This is because the yeast and lactic acid bacteria require a certain level of moisture to function optimally. Water helps to dissolve and transport nutrients, such as starches and sugars, to the enzymes and microorganisms, facilitating the breakdown and fermentation processes.\n\nIn a well-hydrated starter, the yeast can access the starches more efficiently, leading to a faster breakdown of starches and an increase",
